@crswong888 I followed your steps and tried to work it out for my problem. Some problems that I noticed so far are: it only ever seems to converge using PJFNK and not at all using Newton. Also there seems to be some problems whenever there are many constraints.
Could you please take a look at my code? There are the constraint files .h .C, and a mesh + input file. The example I am trying to compute is a simple shear of a unit cell with a stiff fiber inside. A displacement in x direction is applied on the top surface using constraints [topedge_x, topedge_y], while the right and left edge are constrained to be equal. However, the right and left edges behave overly stiff and the simulation does not look right. When I remove the constraints [rightedge_x, rightedge_y], the simulation result looks fine.
Thank you!

FYI this ended up working, thanks for the inspiration! I ended up just having a Receiver (default = 1) postprocessor sent from master to child on timestep_end (which is when I run nekRS), that nekRS then overwrites internally with something like
if (_transfer_in_pp == true)
  setPostprocessorValueByName("transfer_in", false, 0);
else
  return;

// send heat flux in...

Thanks! I'm basically wondering if I can add some type of check like the following:
syncSolutions(Direction)
{
  case ExternalProblem::Direction::TO_EXTERNAL_APP:
  {
    if (!first_step_in_subcycle) // already sent all info to nekRS
      return;

    send_heat_flux_to_nekrs();
    // other stuff in syncSolutions()
  }
}

We'll be running nekRS with a time step about 10x smaller than it's master App, so this could help with speedup.
